segments.text: When he survives and comes back, the board recreated the system administration.
Do you have any idea how that idea came back?
Was that a board idea or do you have any idea?
Well, I think basically was that at that point in time,
They wanted to separate the presidency of Texas A&M University from the chancellorship.
And that particular concept, there was a going about of, well, we need an agricultural man.
And who do we want to get this agricultural man with?
Who, all right, who was pushing that idea?
Was that a board?
That was sort of out there.
Probably the board picked it up.
There was certain people that thought maybe we needed an agricultural person to take the thing at the university.
Yeah.
Because it was an agricultural institution.
We'd had
liberal arts people and namely a history man like Jack Williams.
And so that's essentially was the decision in which it went.
All right, as the board is getting ready for the meeting where they're going to decide who the new president is going to be,
Were you aware of any kind of plan for who might be that new president in 1977?
77, yes indeed.
How were you aware of it?
Well, people told you.
I was on the opposite side.
Okay.
As a matter of fact, they were going down and picking a person that was reporting to me.
And I knew that and I knew the political situations and I could see the actions going across the hall.
As far as you're aware, did he pick them or did they pick him?
Ty Timm was at the heart of all of us.
I did not know that.
This is the chairman of, I mean the department head of agricultural economics.
Agricultural economics.
They said, well, we want to have somebody in agriculture, and of course the best person that we can get in agriculture is an agricultural economist.
This was Ty Timm.
And Ty Timm thought, well, who do we have that we can push forward in this situation?
Well, Carver's name came up.

at that point in time there was designated contacts that were made at that at a group meeting and I am at that it was Shipley's Donut Shop and Bob Cherry had one Pat Wooten had some contacts to be made and and so it went well Reagan Brown was there and he went to see the governor and governor calls
The chairman of the board would say, I think you ought to consider strongly.
Now, who was the governor then?
Was this Mark White?
No, this was Dolph Briscoe.
Was it Briscoe still?
No.
And how far ahead of time did you hear about this, this plan?
Well, I knew that, I don't know whether it was planned, but I think it was worked out at the board meeting.

I think that the pressure was building and enough and I knew at it because frankly Jarvis walked in and asked me to support him and I hemmed and hawed and that was my end of friendship with Jarvis for a long time.
Because this is a note to the typist, you can include this.
I heard about this plan and the way I heard about it was that various members of Jarvis Miller's staff
were assigned to make phone calls and make contacts and then to check back and see had so-and-so spoken to this one or that one, which board members were in agreement and which ones were not yet.
And I then called a friend that I asked him to never reveal my name and I would never reveal his, but he was a close friend of John Lindsay.
one of our outstanding former students in Houston, and I knew that John Lindsay was very close to Dr. Williams.
And I didn't think Dr. Williams knew about this plan.
And so two or three days after I called this anonymous friend, he called me back and told me that he had passed this information on to Lindsay.
Lindsay had passed it on to President Williams, and Williams had told him that whomever this person was

They didn't know what they were talking about because he was the one to make the recommendation as to who the new president would be to the Board of Regents, and that Jarvis Miller's name had not even been mentioned.
A week later, just before the board meeting, I got a second call from this anonymous friend in which Williams had called John Lindsay back and said, I'm being overwhelmed.
Phone calls, letters, telegrams, and everything else.
My arm is being broken at the socket.
What was the general reaction as far as you were aware in agriculture on campus and off campus?
I think general reaction, at least to start with, was good acceptance.
And when Jarvis came in, did he attempt to change anything in agriculture?
Well, yes.

I mean, he attempted to change the structure because at the time the Jarvis came in, I was the Experiment Station Director reported to me, the Extension Director reported to me, and he was going to take those out and put those into vice presidents, namely Perry Atkinson, and then he picked an associate vice president, namely O.D.
Butler, who he thought would be able to handle the extension pieces of this kind of thing.
And they would report directly to him?
And they would report directly to him.
Around you as the dean?
Around me as the dean, and I would report to the regular dean, the academic approach, because he had, Mac Prescott was named academic vice president shortly thereafter.
Let's back up.
While Cal, under Dr. Williams, John C. Calhoun had been vice president for academic affairs.
Describe what it was like to be a dean
reporting to Dr. Calhoun?
It was an interesting kind of a thing.
Dr. Calhoun was generally straightforward and accepted, and we could discuss things, but occasionally he would blow his top.
Just a second, let me be sure that I didn't turn this thing.
He would lose his temper, I should say.
Calhoun did?
Yeah.
Oh, let's see.
I never saw that.
Go ahead.
And he would come down on you, but almost immediately thereafter, it was a matter forgotten, and the issues began.
Work was the thing, so you could work with the fellow.
During those, Calhoun...
I had a lot of confidence in John Calhoun.
During those Calhoun-Williams years, who were your favorite, I'm not going to ask you the negative, who were your favorite dean colleagues, the ones that were best to work with?
I'm not sure I had a favorite.
Meaning you liked them all?
I generally liked them all.
I mean, we got along all right.
Although sometimes the votes in those days used to be 10 to 1.
Do you remember any important idea you had that Calhoun didn't accept?
Calhoun and Williams?
Not really.
They had some ideas that I wouldn't accept.
And it passed on.
Such as?
Well, that we didn't need all these animals, as far as this is concerned.
We could use artificial types of things and animals, using the petroleum engineering as a model in his own mind.
Were we making real progress in those years, the Rudder-Williams years?
Oh, yes.
In hindsight, how well prepared for the job was Williams for A&M at the time he was here?
Dr. Williams was the man for the time.
I sure feel that way.
He was the man.
John Calhoun was the man for the time.
And I didn't feel pushback or anything of a sort relative to the, relative to working with either one of the two.
And I had more difficulty with Jarvis Miller because obviously I was, I didn't generally consider him as presidential material.
Maybe you ought not put that in.
As far as you know, what was the process Jarvis used to select the new vice president of academic affairs?
He listened to me.
Did he?
Okay.
All right.
Did he call and ask advice?
No, I volunteered it.
Oh, okay.
All right.
And the reason why I volunteered it is that I wanted a friend in that office.
Oh, okay.
All right.
All right.
Who else did you think might have been selected?
I don't know.
I really didn't question it at all.
Okay.
Because, you see, Mack was president, was dean of science.
He would be well accepted.
He was well accepted on the campus and things.
Did Jarvis give you and or Mac give you deans any directions of what to do or not to do?
Occasionally we'd get small pieces of advice and most of it would be policy discussions and this kind of a thing.
But did things continue to function pretty well?
I thought they functioned a lot better than I thought they would because at that point in time I
My profile became much lower than it had been.
Alright, and the reorganizational change did occur.
It occurred.
It occurred.
And am I correct that those, the two directors, Experiment Station and Extension Service, in fact though, instead of reporting to Jarvis,
ended up reporting to the system, didn't they?
That was after a time, and I'm not quite sure I understand what process went through along this particular line.
But they, whether it was because Clyde Freeman was in the system office and there was a growing
tagging, there was growing friction between Jarvis Miller and Frank Hubert.
After, after Dr. Williams.
Yeah, and that, that Frank Hubert went up and suggested the rearrangement, and so
Atkinson and Butler, instead of being vice presidents, became vice chancellors and reported directly to the chancellor.
And essentially that is the structure that is, which we've inherited so far.
The major change happened in 1988.
when Charles Arntzen came in as Deputy Chancellor, or whatever they called him, of Agriculture, and he became Dean at that point.
When I retired as Dean, and he picked up the Dean's title, he had the Directorship title, and only a couple of years ago, or years ago, Hyler has picked up the Extension Director title.
When those two administrative units were separated out of your authority under Dr. Miller, was it more difficult then to get the regular task of agriculture accomplished?
Yes, I think so, because you had to deal with other people and had to convince other people.
In the early days, there were certain things that O.D.
Butler had on his agenda, and he was able to work with Perry Atchison to get those into the play.
And I didn't particularly agree with that approach at all.
And so the only thing is that I just took it to a point and dropped the matter.
And usually sometime later, it fell my duty to clean up the mess.
Were you and other deans aware of Dr. Miller's approaching problems with the board?
Yes, I was.
Because I had, I was called aside by Frank Hubert.
In advance?
In advance.
Are you at liberty to say how far?
Days?
Hours?
It was a month or so.
Oh, okay.
Okay.
See, the fundamental issue as far as I was able to determine was that
In the utilization of funding, historically, there has always been amount of the available fund made available into the budget of the university.
And presidents like Rudder and Williams always turned a lot of that back.
But Jarvis and Mac Prescott decided, well, it had been appropriated.
They were going to spend it.
And this, of course, horrified Clyde Freeman, as it never had been before, because it was always been a working gentleman's agreement that that money would come back and do this kind of thing.
So they began to press Jarvis to stop spending this money.
And Jarvis simply said no.
He had the authority, and he proceeded to go ahead and do it.
And so I think that was at the heart.
There may have been other aspects that were at the heart of the situation.
But I was called in by the chancellor.
Well, actually, I wasn't called in.
The legislature was going on at that particular point, and there was a hearing on the real estate center.
And the chancellor was there, and he said, what am I going to do?
I said, I don't know.
I said, you need somebody that Jarvis appreciates and to move the, to get him to work with you.
because when I was, when he reported to me, I didn't, I normally just took things over and said, okay, you do it, and he did it.
And I think there may have been some feeling as far as this is concerned.
All right, then the official action to terminate Dr. Miller as president
occurred in the in June of 1980.
It was 1980.
I was I was in Mexico at the time.
How'd you hear about it?
The secretary called.
He got me on the phone and told me about it.
Were, so, and the appointment of Chuck Sampson, were you and other deans surprised at Chuck's appointment?
I was, yes.
Chuck, I heard that.
The, did, did Dr. Sampson, when you got back from Mexico, was there any change in the,
None whatsoever, except that Sampson asked me to come up and explain the program that I was in, where my goals were, and things of this sort.
All right, and then after about a year, Vandiver is selected.
How did he introduce himself to you and the other key administrators on the campus?
Let's see, what was it?
There was a problem that existed shortly after he became president.
And there was, I don't recall, and the whole faculty met.
And that was essentially the first time I'd heard of Vandiver.
How did he do with the whole faculty?
Well, he offered to resign.
And the faculty, almost unanimously, came up and started, you know, some of us said, well, what's going on here?
And so one or two people start standing up and said, we're for you.
And then so they sort of had the crowd.
So that was the end of that situation.
But I don't recall the details of the problem.
Did you take him, did he travel around to see all the centers?
He traveled around to see the centers.
He and I had, I enjoyed working with him.
particularly in certain international situations that we got and we resolved some international programs together.
We had a problem that occurred in Saudi Arabia and I

I finally just decided I was going to, they came in and talked to me, and I just finally just went in to President Vandiver and said, look, just make me chair in charge of this particular program until I can get it settled.
And he did, and then he immediately went to Saudi Arabia and shook hands with those people, and everything was settled.
Dr. Prescott was the Vice President of Academic Affairs.
and during those Miller and early Vandiver years and so I'm assuming that he understood agriculture well.
He understood it a lot better and he was he was clearly a friend.
And then who follows him?
Who's after after Mack who is the next?
I don't recall.
And you're dean until 88?
I'm dean until February 29, 1988.
During those years, do you feel that we would have made more progress if the old administrative structure had still been in place?
Of the same academic person being responsible for the college, the...
station and the service?
Maybe, maybe not.
I don't know.
I did the best I could under the circumstances.
I had a great deal to do with hiring faculty and appointment of heads of departments and things of this sort.
So as far as the college itself is concerned,
in the college during those years particularly, who are some of the, as you look back, who are some of the greatest appointments you are proud to claim?
Well, I was glad to appoint Perry Atkinson as head of department.
I know the answers to this, but why?
Why would you be proud of Perry Atkinson?
Well, he was a man who knew both the practical and the science.
Was he congenial to work with?
Yes, he was.
We worked together.
Fact is, almost a day after I was appointed, in fact, the day before I became appointed, it was announced, and that wasn't even the place.
I went down to South Texas, and we fought a battle down there together.
We fought many battles together, because seemingly entomologists always invented a new problem.

uh because Perry a truly outstanding researcher am I correct in that yes but also up to the time he was uh doing his research when he went into administration he lost his yeah and he came back it was uh but at the same time he seemed to me to be realistic is that right you have to say that you have to say that
I think the only thing I regret as far as his chancellorship was concerned is that he up and left it.
And as a matter of fact, he left Dean Charlie Arnson up high and dry.
What about other key appointments that you're proud of to look back on?
Well, I think Gene Sanders was one of them.
What was his department?
His biochemistry, biophysics at that particular point, was one because he made a change that I wanted to make, and that's kind of a thing.
Zerl Carpenter was a good man, but he didn't last long because they took him and made him director of the Extension Service.
And Zerl was in what department?
He was in animal science.
Animal science.
Did he follow OD?
He followed OD.
Let's go back and describe O.D.
Butler as a department head.
His manner and style, strengths, weaknesses, if he had any.
O.D.
Butler had a wealth of ideas.
And what he needed most was somebody to filter them.
Was there ever such a person?
There was.
Who?
Me.
Oh, okay, okay.
Yeah, as dean.
As dean, yeah, yeah.
And he would carry on and we worked together.
We put this, essentially made the movement together to put this building in place.
And he had, it was, I admired him as far as this was concerned.
And he was a
strong-willed leader of the department wasn't he?

He was a strong-willed leader he did some things that I don't think were very good things to do but he his problem was fundamentally he was a strong-willed leader he was a charismatic leader in a way but O.D.
Butler principal problem was that he experienced
In other words, his academic experience was largely A&M and a year or two at Michigan State.
And as a result, his vision of what could be in terms of a larger major university was somewhat smaller than
So, all right, then describe what would be the ideal experience for a key leader at a school like Texas A&M.
Where should they have been?
I think they need to be at one of the major land-grant universities.
Bowen came from Oklahoma State, fine.
And I would name those universities as being Cornell, Rutgers, Penn State, Virginia Tech, Florida, maybe Wisconsin.
Wisconsin's problem is their undergraduate program.
Their graduate program is superb.
Cal Davis.
Minnesota.
Michigan State?
I meant to mention Michigan State, yeah.
I did not mean to leave them out.
I think Iowa State has moved a great deal forward.
For a long while they were falling back pretty heavily.
I don't know about Illinois.
I don't know about Purdue.
Do you think in terms of say agriculture,
I'm thinking in terms yeah basically but nonetheless I'm thinking in terms of the land-grant concept.
Do you think Texas A&M has a chance in year 2020 to be one of the top 10 public institutions?
Oh I expect so public yes top 10 is a pretty large number
Because I think that Florida, NC State, Arizona, and Washington among the publics are now making real progress.
University of Washington, not Washington State.
No, no, not Washington State.
That they are really moving upward as publics, as we are moving upward.
But then to be in the top ten, then you've got to crowd some of those others out.
Yeah, that's going to be difficult to do.
We're talking about other key appointments that you're proud to remember and key associates during your deaning years.
I guess I don't...
I have trouble remembering names.
What about some faculty hires that you... Did we go get any true all-stars?
Yeah, we got some all-stars.
Let's see, where's the catalog here?
I'll try that.
I think we have...
I was trying to think of the name.
Did anyone ever try to get you to add any programs that we didn't do at all?
Most of those were some of my own invention.
Such as?
Undergraduate degrees in genetics, degrees in nutrition.
What is the name?
I'm having trouble remembering it.
Max Summers is the one I was thinking of.
What's his specialty?
Etymology.
We hired him cheaply from the University of Texas.
Perry hired him.
He came in and, of course, he's a member of the National Academy now.
See, I have a theory that the way to really attract national attention quickly is to hire a few stars.
But he wasn't a star when he came here.
But he was about to be, wasn't he?
Wasn't he about to be?
Wasn't he clearly on the way?
I think he was on the way up, but as I said, we hired him rather inexpensively.
And of course, he's come along since that particular point in time.
Now, during those years, you were dean for how many years?
Twenty years.
I was acting dean from September 1, 67 to February 28.
So were you the longest serving dean in modern times at A&M?
In agriculture.
Or any other?
Who else served longer than 20?
Well, Kyle.
Oh, okay.
Some of the early ones.
Yeah, but in the last 40, 50 years, has anybody been a dean for 20 years?
21, 20 and a half years.
During the time when you were dean, what was your normal workday routine?
What time did you get up and get to the office?
I got to the office generally about 8.30.
I was never here at 8, never in the office at 8.
And what was...
